s: In any case, I didn't hold Russell Brand in very high regard as someone who should be taken seriously as a comic much less a political critic. His humor seemed manic, tortured and over-compensating and sometimes just mean. He just wasn't funny to me. So, when his name came up in the context of politics, I was intrigued. What, I wondered, could such a person have to say that would make anyone, much less the BBC, want to listen other than pure celebrity? This book, Revolution...
